<body>
    <header>
        <h1>Oestrous Cycle Study Guide</h1>
        <p>Your comprehensive resource for understanding cattle reproduction.</p>
    </header>
    <main>
        <h2>Phases of the Oestrous Cycle</h2>
        <div class="phase">
            <h3>1. Proestrus (Days 18-20)</h3>
            <p>
                The <span class="highlight">decline in progesterone (P4)</span> due to luteolysis allows an increase in <span class="highlight">GnRH</span>, which stimulates the release of <span class="highlight">FSH</span> and <span class="highlight">LH</span>. The dominant follicle (DF) grows, producing high levels of <span class="highlight">oestrogen (E2)</span>, preparing for ovulation.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="phase">
            <h3>2. Dioestrus (Days 5-17)</h3>
            <p>
                This phase is dominated by <span class="highlight">progesterone (P4)</span> produced by the corpus luteum (CL). P4 suppresses GnRH to inhibit further follicular growth and ovulation. If no pregnancy occurs, <span class="highlight">PGF2α</span> triggers CL regression.
            </p>
        </div>
        
        <h2>Follicular Waves</h2>
        <div class="wave">
            <h3>How Follicular Waves Work</h3>
            <p>
                Cows exhibit <span class="highlight">2 or 3 follicular waves</span> per cycle:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Recruitment:</strong> FSH stimulates a group of follicles to grow.</li>
                <li><strong>Selection:</strong> One follicle becomes dominant, producing E2 and inhibin.</li>
                <li><strong>Dominance:</strong> The dominant follicle suppresses others and ovulates if progesterone declines.</li>
                <li><strong>Atresia:</strong> Non-dominant follicles regress due to insufficient hormonal support.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        
        <div class="hormones">
            <h3>Key Hormones in the Cycle</h3>
            <p>
                <strong>1. Progesterone (P4):</strong> Produced by the CL; inhibits GnRH.<br>
                <strong>2. Oestrogen (E2):</strong> Produced by the dominant follicle; stimulates LH surge.<br>
                <strong>3. FSH:</strong> Stimulates follicular recruitment and early growth.<br>
                <strong>4. LH:</strong> Maintains dominant follicle and triggers ovulation.<br>
                <strong>5. PGF2α:</strong> Causes CL regression if no pregnancy occurs.<br>
            </p>
        </div>
    </main>
